# 1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)

## 🔹 What are Emergency Provisions?

Emergency provisions allow the Union Government to gain extra powers during extraordinary situations.

📌 Mentioned in:

### **Part XVIII (Articles 352–360)**

---

# 🔵 Types of Emergencies

| Type                               | Article |
| ---------------------------------- | ------- |
| National Emergency                 | 352     |
| State Emergency (President’s Rule) | 356     |
| Financial Emergency                | 360     |

---

# 🔴 1️⃣ National Emergency (Article 352)

Declared during:

* War
* External aggression
* Armed rebellion

📌 Earlier term “internal disturbance” replaced by:
👉 Armed rebellion (44th Amendment)

---

## Effects

* Centre becomes powerful
* Fundamental Rights may be restricted
* Parliament gains authority over State List

---

# 🔹 Approval

Must be approved by Parliament within:
👉 1 month

Requires:
👉 Special majority

---

# 🔵 2️⃣ State Emergency / President’s Rule (Article 356)

Declared when:
👉 Constitutional machinery fails in state.

Based on:

* Governor’s report
  OR
* Otherwise

---

## Effects

* State government dismissed
* Parliament controls state legislature

📌 Most controversial emergency provision.

---

# 🔴 3️⃣ Financial Emergency (Article 360)

Declared when:
👉 Financial stability threatened.

Effects:

* Centre controls state finances
* Salary reduction possible

📌 Never declared in India till now.

---

# 🔹 Revocation of Emergency

* President can revoke anytime
* Lok Sabha can also disapprove National Emergency

---

# 🔹 Important Amendments

## 44th Amendment

Added safeguards:

* Cabinet advice compulsory
* Rights protection strengthened

📌 Important UPSC area.

---

# 🔹 Important Facts

| Emergency        | Important Point |
| ---------------- | --------------- |
| National         | Article 352     |
| President’s Rule | Article 356     |
| Financial        | Article 360     |

